<methodology slug="ops-annual-planning-process">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>gtm-strategist</domain>
    <summary>Five-stage planning framework: Reflect, Envision, Strategize, Plan, Execute with enforced ≤3 annual priorities, quantified KRs with kill-switches and leading indicators.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>planning</tag>
      <tag>okr</tag>
      <tag>annual</tag>
      <tag>strategy</tag>
      <tag>execution</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="ops-annual-planning-templates"/>
      <ref slug="growth-gtm-strategy"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Annual Planning Process</title>

    <summary>A structured five-stage planning framework for solopreneurs: Reflect (year-in-review with cited metrics), Envision (12-month vision statement), Strategize (max 3 priorities — hard cap enforced), Plan (annual → quarterly → monthly task tree), Execute (weekly/monthly/quarterly review rhythm). The non-negotiable rule: cap annual priorities at 3 and enforce a quantified kill-switch and leading indicator for each key result.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Founders who plan day-to-day without a yearly direction accumulate effort without compounding. Annual planning forces a "stop doing" list, exposes misallocated time, and creates quarterly checkpoints that surface drift before it becomes permanent. LLM-generated plans without forced prioritization converge on 7-item lists where nothing is real. The ≤3 priority constraint is the mechanism that makes the plan actionable.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>December/January: annual review + goal setting</item>
        <item>End of each quarter: quarterly review + next-quarter plan</item>
        <item>First week of each month: monthly check-in against quarterly goals</item>
        <item>When metrics show meaningful drift from targets (&gt;15% off expected)</item>
        <item>Decomposing an annual goal into a monthly/weekly task tree</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting the founder's vision — agents produce regression-to-mean prose; founders write vision, agents critique and operationalize</item>
        <item>Strategic pivots based on new market signal — qualitative, narrative, requires founder ownership</item>
        <item>Personal goals (energy, satisfaction, burnout) — agents have no telemetry on these</item>
        <item>Salary, equity, or capital-allocation decisions inside the plan — financial-planning domain</item>
        <item>Org-wide planning at more than 20 people — use PM-agile or PM-traditional methodologies instead</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="process-stages">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap annual priorities at exactly 3. If more than 3 priorities are proposed, refuse to proceed until one is dropped. Do not silently accept a 4th priority.</statement>
        <rationale>More than 3 annual priorities dilutes focus to the point where nothing compounds. The constraint is the mechanism that makes the plan actionable. LLMs default to 7-item lists; the cap must be enforced in prompts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Reflect: pull full-year metrics, identify wins/challenges/surprises, produce year-in-review with cited data</item>
        <item>Envision: write a vivid 12-month vision statement — what you will have, why it matters, what success feels like (founder writes, agent critiques)</item>
        <item>Strategize: select 3 strategic priorities; for each, answer: what is the biggest constraint on growth? what would 10x the business? what should you stop doing?</item>
        <item>Plan: break annual goals into quarterly milestones, monthly focus areas, and weekly task trees (cascade only to month — weekly/daily emerge from context)</item>
        <item>Execute: run weekly (30 min), monthly (2 hours), quarterly (half-day), and annual (1-2 days) reviews on fixed calendar dates</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="planning-calendar">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Schedule all four review cadences (weekly, monthly, quarterly, annual) on the calendar before the year starts. Agent holds the slot but humans must show up; agent must not skip a human review even if metrics look fine.</statement>
        <rationale>Cadence drift — monthly check-ins compressed to Slack messages, quarterly reviews skipped — is the primary cause of plans becoming irrelevant by Q2. Calendar commitment is the only reliable mechanism.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Week 1 of December: begin annual review</item>
        <item>Week 2 of December: finish review, start next-year planning</item>
        <item>Weeks 3-4 of December: finalize annual plan</item>
        <item>Week 1 of January: Q1 detailed planning</item>
        <item>End of each quarter: quarterly review</item>
        <item>First week of each month: monthly check-in</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="key-results-criteria">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every key result must have: a numeric target with unit and date, a current baseline, a measurable data source available at reporting time, and a kill-switch (when do we stop this initiative?) and a leading indicator (what changes first if we are wrong?).</statement>
        <rationale>KRs without these fields cannot be scored objectively. "Improve customer experience meaningfully" is decoration. "Increase NPS from 32 to 45 by Q3, measured monthly via Delighted" is a KR.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define the metric layer (which tool is the source of truth for each KR) at the start of the year. Lock definitions before Q1 starts and never silently change them mid-year.</statement>
        <rationale>Goal scoring against shifting definitions is misleading. "Customer" in January must mean the same thing in December.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="saas-annual-plan-example">
      <example type="good" title="SaaS $50K→$100K ARR annual plan">
        <note>Vision: reach $100K ARR with sustainable solo operation. Annual goals: ARR $50K to $100K, customers 100 to 200, churn 5% to 3%. Quarterly breakdown: Q1 improve retention (reduce churn to 3%); Q2 double down on content marketing; Q3 launch premium tier; Q4 optimize and scale ads. Each quarter has one primary theme and 2-3 key results with numeric targets.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="info-product-annual-plan-example">
      <example type="good" title="Info-product $80K→$200K revenue annual plan">
        <note>Vision: build evergreen course business with $200K revenue. Annual goals: revenue $80K to $200K, courses 1 to 3, email list 5K to 15K. Quarterly breakdown: Q1 launch course #2; Q2 build email list to 10K; Q3 launch course #3; Q4 evergreen funnel optimization. The quarterly sequence respects dependencies — list-building (Q2) before launch (Q3).</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="common-planning-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Plan has 6 annual priorities and no "not doing this year" list.</description>
        <reason>Six priorities means nothing is prioritized. Without a stop-doing list, the founder keeps all existing commitments plus adds new ones. Compounding never happens.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Quarterly plan decomposes into daily task lists generated in January.</description>
        <reason>Daily tasks from January are stale by March. Cascade only to monthly level; weekly and daily plans emerge from current context, not annual planning.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Year-in-review contains only wins. Churned customers and missed targets are not mentioned.</description>
        <reason>Survivorship bias in annual reviews produces optimistic plans that ignore the mechanisms of past failure. Year-in-review must include lost-deal and churned-customer themes.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Annual plan has financial and product goals but no personal goals (energy, satisfaction, burnout).</description>
        <reason>Founder burnout kills the plan. A solopreneur's sustainability is a business risk, not a soft concern.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-integration">
      <p>A cron-driven planning subagent runs: (1) annually in early December — pulls full-year metrics, drafts year-in-review, opens a planning doc with template; (2) quarterly — produces a review packet 1 week before quarter-end; (3) monthly — runs a 30-min check-in script with goal-progress diff; (4) weekly — prepares a "this week vs this quarter" snapshot. Each output is a draft for human review, never an autonomous decision. A separate "guardrail" pass red-teams the plan: flags too-many-priorities, missing kill-switches, undefined metrics.</p>

      <p>Goal: produce year-in-review draft for [Year]. Inputs: monthly metric exports (revenue, customers, churn, MRR, ARPU); CRM win/loss notes; sprint retros. Method: compute YoY deltas; surface 3 wins, 3 challenges, 3 surprises with CITED data; flag any metric definition that changed mid-year. Constraints: no more than 1 page; every claim sourced; mark "ASSUMPTION" when data missing.</p>

      <p>Goal: red-team annual plan v1. Method: enumerate 5 ways this plan fails by Q3. For each, name the leading indicator, the kill-switch, and the alternative. Refuse: if priorities &gt; 3, refuse and ask user to drop one; do not silently accept. Output: risk register; do not edit the plan.</p>

      <p>LLM-generated OKRs are vague ("improve customer experience") and uncalibrated. Without explicit targets + measurement plan, they are decoration. Year-in-review summaries selectively pick wins, mirror founder bias, and miss negative signals (rising churn, declining cohort retention). Cascading goals (annual → quarterly → monthly → weekly) becomes a rigid Gantt chart that ignores Q1 learnings affecting Q3-4. The methodology says "build in flexibility" — agents tend to over-specify. Prioritization to ≤3 priorities is hard for LLMs — they list 7. Force-rank constraint must be enforced in prompts. Cadence drift: monthly check-ins skip, quarterly reviews compress into Slack messages. Agent reminders help; agent decisions don't. Metric definitions drift over the year (what counted as a "customer" in Jan ≠ Dec). Goal tracking against shifting denominators is misleading.</p>

      <p>Lock the metric layer (dbt / Cube semantic layer / spreadsheet of definitions) at the start of the year. Goal scoring fails when definitions drift. Cap priorities to ≤3 annual, ≤3 per quarter. Codify the limit in the planning prompt. Pair every KR with a kill-switch (when do we stop?) and a leading indicator (what changes first if we are wrong?). Schedule reviews on the calendar before the year starts; agent can hold the slot but humans must show up. Keep the annual doc a living artifact: monthly delta entries instead of rewrites. History is the asset. Separate quantitative goals (revenue, customers) from systems goals (e.g. "launch retention dashboard") — methodology blends them; agents should tag. Always include a "stop doing" list. The methodology's "what should you stop doing?" is the easiest to skip; force the agent to surface candidates.</p>

      <p>LLMs auto-hedge: "increase revenue meaningfully". Force quantification (number + unit + date) or reject the KR. Year-in-review pulls survivorship bias — winners loud, losers buried. Always include lost-deal + churned-customer themes. Cascading too far. Daily tasks generated by an LLM in January are stale by March. Cascade only to month; let weekly/daily emerge. "Stretch goals" become anchors; teams hit ~70% of stretch and feel like they failed. Use 1.0 = ambitious-but-credible, not 0.7. Multi-year compounding: agent sets unrealistic Y2/Y3 trajectory based on Y1 outlier. Check growth assumptions against industry benchmarks (OpenView SaaS, Bessemer Cloud Index). Calendar-driven reminders work; calendar-driven decisions don't. Agent should never skip a human review even if metrics look fine. Be wary of the agent generating "vision" prose — it converges on bland mission-statement style. Vision is a founder artifact; agent is editor not author. Don't let agent close objectives early. Closure is a human decision tied to evidence + retro; auto-closing on metric hit hides drift in inputs.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/monthly-checkin.py" purpose="Monthly check-in calculator: actual vs expected KR progress with on-track/at-risk/off-track status"/>
    </templates>

